A closure is a function that retains access to its lexical scope even when the function is executed outside that scope.
 Example:

function outer() {
    let count = 0;
    return function inner() {
        count++;
        return count;
    };
}

const counter = outer();
console.log(counter()); // 1
console.log(counter()); // 2
console.log(counter()); // 3

In this example, 'inner' is a closure that has access to 'count' from 'outer', allowing it to maintain state between calls.

Polymorphism is a core concept in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) that allows objects of different classes to be treated as objects of a common superclass. It enables methods to perform different functions based on the object that invokes them, enhancing flexibility and extensibility in the code.

There are two main types of polymorphism:

1. Method Overloading: This occurs when multiple methods in the same class have the same name but different parameter lists (different types or number of parameters). The appropriate method is selected based on the arguments passed during the method call.

Example:

class MathOperations {
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

MathOperations math = new MathOperations();
math.add(5, 10); // Calls the first add method
math.add(5.5, 10.2); // Calls the second add method

2. Method Overriding: This occurs when a subclass provides a specific implementation of a method that is already defined in its superclass. The overridden method in the subclass has the same name, return type, and parameters as the method in the superclass. When the method is called on an object of the subclass, the subclass's version is executed.

Example:

class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

Animal myDog = new Dog();
myDog.sound(); // Outputs: Dog barks

